WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.680
So, yes, I work on the tidymodels team at Posit, and in a previous role I did data science

00:00:07.680 --> 00:00:14.280
consultancy, and one of the clients we worked with was a subscription-based business, and

00:00:14.280 --> 00:00:20.160
they were sort of just starting out, building out their data team, and several of the questions

00:00:20.160 --> 00:00:26.100
they had that they wanted to answer with data were sort of centered around customer journey.

00:00:26.100 --> 00:00:31.780
So one of them was who was likely to cancel their subscription any time soon, and another

00:00:31.780 --> 00:00:38.500
thing that they were interested in was how long somebody would stay as a customer overall.

00:00:38.500 --> 00:00:44.240
And they did not use survival analysis for this, even though you can answer both of these

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:47.060
questions with one model.

00:00:47.060 --> 00:00:52.820
And the reason that they didn't was that they didn't think it applied.

00:00:52.820 --> 00:00:55.700
So if you were just suddenly a little bit surprised about why the hell is she talking

00:00:55.700 --> 00:00:59.619
about survival analysis, I get it.

00:00:59.619 --> 00:01:05.739
And that's why I'm here with just a little bit of a push for a slight rebrand, because

00:01:05.739 --> 00:01:09.580
I would like to talk about this through the lens of the data.

00:01:09.580 --> 00:01:16.699
And the data is time-to-event data, and that event can really be a lot of different things.

00:01:16.699 --> 00:01:18.540
It could be a customer journey.

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:27.320
It could also be your employees' thing, or a machine needing repairs or replacement.

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:30.139
It could be pets getting adopted.

00:01:30.139 --> 00:01:38.519
It could be complaints being processed, or, yes, death, hence the maybe overly successful

00:01:38.519 --> 00:01:41.339
name for the methodology here.

00:01:41.339 --> 00:01:47.059
But I'm most definitely not here to point fingers at that data science team, because

00:01:47.059 --> 00:01:53.339
we very famously know all models are wrong, and some are useful, and they were definitely

00:01:53.339 --> 00:01:56.339
getting some use out of the models that they used.

00:01:56.339 --> 00:02:07.260
I'm just here to offer you methodology tailor-made for this problem, sort of forged in the fires

00:02:07.260 --> 00:02:12.220
of situations where it is really about life and death.

00:02:12.220 --> 00:02:18.179
And I want to build some intuition with you here for that kind of data, what kind of challenges

00:02:18.179 --> 00:02:22.179
come with it, and how that methodology addresses it.

00:02:22.179 --> 00:02:27.860
And of course, I'm also here to show you how to do that with tidy models.

00:02:27.860 --> 00:02:33.940
We've worked on integrating that in the framework, so that it just walks and talks and feels

00:02:34.179 --> 00:02:41.059
like other elements of tidy models, essentially giving you another tool in your toolbox for

00:02:41.059 --> 00:02:45.500
situations when you encounter this type of data.

00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:54.179
So let's look at these questions that they had, and why maybe some standard tools don't

00:02:54.179 --> 00:02:56.820
quite give you what you're actually looking for.

00:02:56.820 --> 00:03:03.500
So the first one of these was how long somebody's going to stay as a customer.

00:03:03.500 --> 00:03:08.020
And we might have several observations over a time length.

00:03:08.020 --> 00:03:12.940
People show up, have a subscription, eventually cancel that and leave.

00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:16.059
Some stay longer, some stay shorter.

00:03:16.059 --> 00:03:18.500
That is a numeric value.

00:03:18.500 --> 00:03:22.940
You might be thinking, well, I'll do a regression on this.

00:03:22.940 --> 00:03:25.179
Yes, you can.

00:03:25.179 --> 00:03:31.259
But you should keep in mind that that time window is the observation time.

00:03:31.259 --> 00:03:36.179
It is not time to event, time until somebody cancels.

00:03:36.179 --> 00:03:40.699
There's no notion of event if you're just looking at this, right?

00:03:40.699 --> 00:03:45.500
So we incorporate that in my cute little drawing.

00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:49.979
We might have situations where somebody comes and then eventually leaves.

00:03:49.979 --> 00:03:51.059
That's like the black dot.

00:03:51.059 --> 00:03:53.580
That's where we observe the event that we're interested in.

00:03:53.580 --> 00:04:01.100
And that middle row, that person showed up and is still here when we're at now.

00:04:01.100 --> 00:04:02.380
So there's still a customer.

00:04:02.380 --> 00:04:04.339
That's pretty good.

00:04:04.339 --> 00:04:08.899
This type of observation is what we call censored because we haven't observed the full time

00:04:08.899 --> 00:04:11.500
until the event.

00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:21.339
If you're taking your time here and then run your model and interpret it as time to event,

00:04:21.339 --> 00:04:27.380
you're making an implicit assumption that everything is an event, including the customer

00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:28.859
that is still here.

00:04:28.859 --> 00:04:34.019
So you're sort of underestimating the length of time that they stay on just because you're

00:04:34.019 --> 00:04:35.059
like, oh, it's now.

00:04:35.059 --> 00:04:36.140
It's a cutoff.

00:04:36.140 --> 00:04:39.000
I'm saying you left.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:43.779
So maybe that's not ideal and that's not what you want to be doing.

00:04:43.779 --> 00:04:48.779
An alternative approach that possibly comes to mind here is to say, okay, well, then I'm

00:04:48.779 --> 00:04:51.579
just leaving those observations.

00:04:51.579 --> 00:04:56.779
But that information is there and you're not randomly leaving out data.

00:04:56.779 --> 00:04:59.899
You're leaving out very specific observations.

00:04:59.899 --> 00:05:04.619
So you're biasing your results in that regard too.

00:05:04.619 --> 00:05:07.700
Sort of side note, could also be like, okay, fine.

00:05:07.700 --> 00:05:14.339
I'll wait until I see all of my observations, all of my events, especially in that example

00:05:14.339 --> 00:05:19.660
that is also maybe like not what you want to be doing, waiting until all of your customers

00:05:19.660 --> 00:05:23.079
have left, right?

00:05:23.079 --> 00:05:32.480
So you can do things, but I hopefully get the point across that they don't quite fit.

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:38.519
When we look at the other question, who is likely to stop being a customer?

00:05:38.519 --> 00:05:42.079
We can say, yeah, that is a binary event.

00:05:42.079 --> 00:05:44.480
We know how to model binary things.

00:05:44.480 --> 00:05:47.000
Give me a classification model.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:50.839
And you're sort of ignoring the time aspect here.

00:05:50.839 --> 00:05:57.000
And that matters that you're ignoring, because then the question actually becomes, who is

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.359
likely to stop being a customer while we observe them?

00:06:00.359 --> 00:06:04.880
And that observation window could differ wildly.

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:11.200
So maybe also a little bit of a moment in choosing your model.

00:06:11.200 --> 00:06:18.519
And sort of to gather up the aspects from both of these examples is we're met with a

00:06:18.519 --> 00:06:25.839
challenge that our outcome has two aspects, time and event status.

00:06:25.839 --> 00:06:28.040
And our outcome might be censored.

00:06:28.040 --> 00:06:32.679
And then we have an incomplete observation, but it's not a missing observation.

00:06:32.679 --> 00:06:38.920
And that is a difference, and we would like to be able to account for that difference.

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:46.480
In classification and regression, sort of like standard tools, great for many things,

00:06:46.480 --> 00:06:51.799
but they're not directly equipped to deal with either of these two challenges.

00:06:51.799 --> 00:06:58.640
I've sort of given it away already, but survival analysis is the methodology that is made for

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:00.679
these situations.

00:07:00.679 --> 00:07:06.959
It can simultaneously consider if events happen and when the events happen.

00:07:06.959 --> 00:07:10.679
So it captures both of these aspects.

00:07:10.679 --> 00:07:15.799
And now I'm not going to derive survival analysis from first principles all in this talk.

00:07:16.119 --> 00:07:19.119
But I said I do want to build some intuition.

00:07:19.119 --> 00:07:26.559
And the last attempt we took at this was modeling the event outcome.

00:07:26.559 --> 00:07:28.920
But we had like these different time windows.

00:07:28.920 --> 00:07:33.239
Like, yeah, okay, well, let's look at these time windows.

00:07:33.239 --> 00:07:36.679
Let's try to get closer to a good model.

00:07:36.679 --> 00:07:41.200
Well, now I've just been sliding these over, let's start at the same time.

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:45.399
And then I'm going to put a time window over this.

00:07:45.399 --> 00:07:50.000
So we could try to model who is leaving in that window.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.679
That observation on top is clearly leaving.

00:07:52.679 --> 00:07:57.399
The other two are there at the start, and they're still there at the end.

00:07:57.399 --> 00:07:59.160
So they're not leaving.

00:07:59.160 --> 00:08:03.600
So it's a non-event for this time window.

00:08:03.600 --> 00:08:05.399
That could be one model.

00:08:05.399 --> 00:08:08.320
And we could slide the window over.

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:09.720
Do another one.

00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:13.119
Now we encounter a censored observation.

00:08:13.119 --> 00:08:17.399
For that one, we don't know if they would still be around at the window.

00:08:17.399 --> 00:08:19.079
We just, we don't know.

00:08:19.079 --> 00:08:21.640
We don't have the information.

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:24.600
So maybe we're not including it in this.

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:28.519
But mind you, we were able to include it in this.

00:08:28.519 --> 00:08:33.760
So that's at least a little bit better than before.

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:38.520
And looking at this in different time windows gives us different estimates of the probability

00:08:38.520 --> 00:08:43.719
of having an event, or consequently, a probability of not having an event.

00:08:43.719 --> 00:08:49.840
Or sort of in classical methodology, as you speak in this, the probability of survival.

00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:52.159
You haven't had your event yet.

00:08:52.159 --> 00:08:59.320
So we're starting to build up the probability for one time window for another.

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:02.880
And we could combine these and get a view over this.

00:09:02.880 --> 00:09:10.000
And having sort of this step function, this probability of survival over time, now captures

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:16.440
both the time aspect and the event aspect.

00:09:16.440 --> 00:09:22.559
And we are not going to build a series of models.

00:09:22.559 --> 00:09:26.159
That's sort of walking in the right direction, but it's not quite it.

00:09:26.159 --> 00:09:31.219
So it does highlight two of the central ideas for survival analysis, though.

00:09:31.219 --> 00:09:37.460
So for one is, the thing that you're modeling is that survival curve, or derivatives of it,

00:09:37.460 --> 00:09:43.179
because it captures both of the components of your outcome that you're interested in.

00:09:43.179 --> 00:09:50.099
And the censored observations are partially included rather than discarded outright.

00:09:50.099 --> 00:09:57.140
So that's how survival analysis, as methodology for timed event data, addresses these unique

00:09:57.140 --> 00:10:02.380
challenges about how the data just exists.

00:10:02.380 --> 00:10:04.820
And you didn't come for a stats lecture.

00:10:04.820 --> 00:10:06.140
I know.

00:10:06.140 --> 00:10:09.780
So I do have some code for you.

00:10:09.780 --> 00:10:13.020
I have a churn data set here.

00:10:13.020 --> 00:10:19.380
The first column is tenure, how long somebody's been a customer at this company.

00:10:19.380 --> 00:10:25.659
The second one is churn, that's the binary event, yes and no.

00:10:25.659 --> 00:10:29.580
And the first thing we're going to do with this has nothing to do with tidy models, but

00:10:29.580 --> 00:10:35.580
very much with this type of data, which is we're taking these two columns and combining

00:10:35.580 --> 00:10:38.260
it into what is called a serve object.

00:10:38.260 --> 00:10:43.179
That is sort of the standard data structure for this type of data.

00:10:43.179 --> 00:10:46.539
And that will be our response.

00:10:46.539 --> 00:10:49.500
And then yes, we are doing tidy models here.

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:56.539
We can start with the very classic initial split into training and testing data.

00:10:56.539 --> 00:10:59.940
And then we are going to fit one of these models.

00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:03.380
I'm sprinkling in some preprocessing with recipes.

00:11:03.380 --> 00:11:08.419
We are here removing all of the predictors with zero variance because they don't tell

00:11:08.419 --> 00:11:12.539
us anything about our problem.

00:11:12.539 --> 00:11:19.419
And then we have a little bit that's different from classification and regression.

00:11:19.419 --> 00:11:20.940
We have a different type of model.

00:11:20.940 --> 00:11:24.940
It's a proportional hazards model.

00:11:24.940 --> 00:11:27.179
That is one of the most common ones.

00:11:27.179 --> 00:11:34.380
So I sort of think of it as the cousin to a linear model as the workhorse that you can

00:11:34.380 --> 00:11:39.500
drag out and get, it's a good starting point.

00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:43.900
What is different also is the set mode here.

00:11:43.900 --> 00:11:47.580
We're not setting the mode to classification and not to regression because that's what

00:11:47.580 --> 00:11:51.020
I've been talking about for a good 10 minutes.

00:11:51.020 --> 00:11:55.859
It is sensor regression to indicate that our outcome here is a little bit different.

00:11:55.859 --> 00:11:58.780
We're trying something a little bit different.

00:11:58.780 --> 00:12:02.340
But then we're back in very familiar tidy models territory.

00:12:02.340 --> 00:12:06.940
We take in our recipe and our models back and putting it into a workflow.

00:12:06.940 --> 00:12:11.859
And then we can fit the thing on the training data.

00:12:11.940 --> 00:12:19.940
Now we have a fitted model object and I sort of teased already that we can answer both

00:12:19.940 --> 00:12:23.859
of the questions we had with the one model.

00:12:23.859 --> 00:12:30.659
So how long is somebody going to stay as a customer here?

00:12:30.659 --> 00:12:37.020
We can predict that with the prediction type time, sort of shorthand for survival time.

00:12:37.020 --> 00:12:42.619
It gives you a numeric value for how long somebody is likely to stay.

00:12:42.619 --> 00:12:48.859
And the other question was, who's likely to stop being a customer?

00:12:48.859 --> 00:12:54.500
We're going to flip that around and looking at who's likely to stay.

00:12:54.500 --> 00:13:00.659
And that is sort of survival or the probability of survival.

00:13:00.659 --> 00:13:04.859
And that needs to be calculated at a different time point.

00:13:04.859 --> 00:13:08.419
That's why we had the curve.

00:13:08.419 --> 00:13:14.340
Unfortunately, over all of the time points, the very end, the probability of survival

00:13:14.340 --> 00:13:16.260
is zero for all of us.

00:13:16.260 --> 00:13:22.900
So that is the serious note that you need to put into any talk about survival analysis.

00:13:22.900 --> 00:13:28.780
And calculating that probability of survival here at different time points, that is monthly

00:13:28.780 --> 00:13:33.739
here from month one up to 24 for two years time frame.

00:13:33.739 --> 00:13:40.299
And then we get this thing back that has a bunch of tables and a list column.

00:13:40.299 --> 00:13:46.419
And that is because for one observation, we're getting 24 prediction points back.

00:13:46.419 --> 00:13:52.460
And if we take one of these little tables to inspect it a little closely, we can see

00:13:52.460 --> 00:13:57.619
one column is the evaluation time, and the other one is the probability, the predicted

00:13:57.619 --> 00:14:00.260
probability of survival.

00:14:00.260 --> 00:14:06.099
And then we can take these and make and draw the curves if we want to be looking at them.

00:14:06.099 --> 00:14:10.659
So here are some example ones based on that prediction.

00:14:10.659 --> 00:14:14.179
And you can see that the patterns are different.

00:14:14.179 --> 00:14:20.140
People don't all leave at the same, after the same amount of time.

00:14:20.140 --> 00:14:24.140
Therefore the curves also look different.

00:14:24.140 --> 00:14:32.059
So tidy models for timed event data means there's a few specialized parts.

00:14:32.059 --> 00:14:35.700
For one, the models, your outcome is different.

00:14:35.700 --> 00:14:41.380
You need a different model to estimate how this outcome is connected to your predictors.

00:14:41.380 --> 00:14:45.700
In tidy models, you can use parametric models, semi-parametric models, and tree-based models

00:14:45.700 --> 00:14:47.900
for this.

00:14:47.900 --> 00:14:53.820
We do have different prediction types for this slightly different modeling problem.

00:14:53.820 --> 00:14:59.619
So you've seen the two that exist, that we have for all of the models, which is the survival

00:14:59.619 --> 00:15:03.260
time and the probability of survival.

00:15:03.260 --> 00:15:08.099
And then depending on like the model or the engine, you might get some other ones which

00:15:08.099 --> 00:15:11.500
are related to these.

00:15:11.500 --> 00:15:17.020
And if you have an outcome that has a special form, and you have predictions that is a special

00:15:17.020 --> 00:15:25.299
form, and you want to assess how well those models do, you also need special types of

00:15:25.299 --> 00:15:26.299
metrics.

00:15:26.299 --> 00:15:29.419
And that is what Max is going to be talking about after me.

00:15:29.419 --> 00:15:34.619
So I'm just going to be like, there you go, your topic.

00:15:34.619 --> 00:15:41.619
I get to finish on a slightly different note, which is that tidy models for timed event

00:15:41.619 --> 00:15:47.979
data is not just sort of different types of models in sensors and parsnip, different

00:15:47.979 --> 00:15:50.059
types of metrics and yardstick.

00:15:50.059 --> 00:15:57.140
But we also did a little bit of work, mostly behind the scenes here on workflows and tune,

00:15:57.140 --> 00:16:04.159
so that you can combine these models with recipes and resampling and orchestrate everything

00:16:04.159 --> 00:16:11.599
in tune, sort of like your food chain of tidy models is available.

00:16:11.599 --> 00:16:17.119
And because it is a framework and things should work with each other and click together,

00:16:17.119 --> 00:16:23.960
you then also have the possibility to combine your timed event data analysis with some of

00:16:23.960 --> 00:16:26.059
the other specialized tools.

00:16:26.059 --> 00:16:30.039
So if you have spatial data, you could do spatial resampling, you have text data, you

00:16:30.039 --> 00:16:38.359
could generate predictors from that in combination with your timed event model.

00:16:38.359 --> 00:16:46.119
So when I say, it's tidy models for timed event data, I do mean tidy models for timed

00:16:46.119 --> 00:16:47.119
event data.

00:16:47.119 --> 00:16:48.119
Thank you.

00:16:56.119 --> 00:16:57.119
Thank you, Hannah.

00:16:57.119 --> 00:17:01.960
And we do have questions being taken in Slido for both live and virtual attendees.

00:17:01.960 --> 00:17:03.859
The link there is on the screen.

00:17:03.859 --> 00:17:07.959
We have at least a couple of questions since I've last checked.

00:17:07.959 --> 00:17:09.459
I love this first question.

00:17:09.459 --> 00:17:14.800
How does survival analysis perform in a data set with meaningful seasonality, such as January

00:17:14.800 --> 00:17:20.160
versus November?

00:17:20.160 --> 00:17:25.839
I don't think that that is necessarily a question of survival analysis, that the seasonality

00:17:25.839 --> 00:17:30.599
is sort of an effect of your predictors.

00:17:30.599 --> 00:17:39.800
So a step from recipes to turn your dates into appropriate indicators is something that

00:17:39.800 --> 00:17:42.540
you can use here and combine.

00:17:42.540 --> 00:17:48.160
So that could be a good first approach to including the seasonality.

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:49.160
Great.

00:17:49.160 --> 00:17:54.520
And once you have the predicted probability of survival code over time for each customer

00:17:54.520 --> 00:17:59.859
in your churn example, how do you use that to draw inferences about how long a given

00:17:59.859 --> 00:18:00.859
customer will stay?

00:18:00.859 --> 00:18:07.099
Is there a probability threshold or some other sort of technique?

00:18:07.099 --> 00:18:13.939
So for one, typically like how people burn this down to one number is to say, well, what,

00:18:13.939 --> 00:18:15.699
where's the 50% threshold?

00:18:15.699 --> 00:18:16.819
Like what time is that?

00:18:16.819 --> 00:18:22.180
That's your median or mean survival time.

00:18:22.180 --> 00:18:26.140
That is the numeric predictions that you also saw.

00:18:26.140 --> 00:18:31.599
I think the other interesting use of this is to say, right, we know that person has

00:18:31.599 --> 00:18:33.900
already been here for so long.

00:18:33.900 --> 00:18:36.900
What is the probability that they'll leave tomorrow?

00:18:36.900 --> 00:18:39.780
And if that is high, do I want to do something about it?

00:18:39.780 --> 00:18:41.540
Do I want to contact them?

00:18:41.540 --> 00:18:43.739
Do I leave them alone?

00:18:43.739 --> 00:18:49.540
Do I not spend resources on pestering people who I think are very likely to stay?

00:18:49.540 --> 00:18:54.219
So that kind of decision you can make and you have a probability to go with that rather

00:18:54.300 --> 00:18:59.819
than, oh, they're going to be here for 10 months and like, we're getting close.

00:18:59.819 --> 00:19:00.819
Do we need to do something?

00:19:00.819 --> 00:19:01.819
So.

00:19:01.819 --> 00:19:02.819
Perfect.

00:19:02.819 --> 00:19:03.819
Well, thank you, Hannah.

